This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with landmark matching, which is a common task in computer vision applications. It may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as the authors mention the use of back-propagation to calculate gradients. The paper may also be relevant to the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category as it deals with registration of medical images. The use of optimization techniques and numerical methods suggests that the paper may also belong to the numerical analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. Finally, the use of CUDA for parallel computing suggests that the paper may also belong to the distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-category.
